RABIES, ANIMAL - ISRAEL: (CENTRAL) HUMAN EXPOSURE
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu 15 Oct 2009
Source: YNET (Yediot Aharonot daily, Israel) [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS,
edited]
<http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3790717,00.html>


Rabies continues striking; a cow suspected to be hit in Western Galilee
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Agriculture is concerned about the sharp rise in the number
of rabies cases among animals -- 36 cases since the beginning of the
current year [2009]. The last case was discovered in a cattle barn, in
Bustan Hagalil, Western Galilee; the cow's owners had to be vaccinated
[post exposure] and additional precautionary measures taken. The cow, which
died of an unknown illness, was transferred to the central animal-cadaver
destruction facility and was incinerated there without being sampled.
Later, the veterinary practitioner got the details of her clinical signs
and the suspicion for possible rabies was raised and reported to the
veterinary district office. "Because of the seriousness of rabies, the
Ministry of Agriculture's District Veterinary Officer decided to treat the
incident as a case of rabies. A message was forwarded to the Ministry of
Health, which decided, that due to the serious life-threatening risk posed
by the disease, the exposed people would be treated although the case
remained suspected, obviously not confirmed. The local authority decided on
other measures, to vaccinate animals in the region," said the Ministry of
Agriculture.

According to Ministry of Agriculture's information, a steep rise in the
number of rabies cases in animals has been recorded in recent months,
becoming an "almost daily" event. Since the beginning of this year [2009],
36 rabies cases have been detected in animals, 22 of them in dogs, mostly
in the Galilee and Golan Heights. This compares with only 12 cases during
2008, 15 cases in 2005 and 9 in 2006 [total annual numbers).

The last published case involved an infected donkey in the village
Sedot-Micha, near Bet-Shemesh (Jerusalem district; see item 2 below -
Mod.AS]. Last month [September 2009], 9 people were bitten during one night
by infected jackals in the Afula-Nazareth area [northern Israel].

[byline: Ahiam Rabd, Meital Yasur-Beit Or]

